An Act relative to pupil dental health.
Be it enacted by the Senate and House of Representatives in General Court assembled, and by the authority
of the same, as follows:
1 SECTION 1: Chapter 71 Section 57 of the General Laws is hereby amended by inserting
2 the following after the first paragraph:
3 Upon entering kindergarten or within 30 days of the start of the school year, the parent or
4 guardian of each child shall present to school health personnel certification that the child within
5 the previous 12 months has received a dental screening by a qualified licensed dental
6 professional that was performed no earlier than 12 months prior to the date of initial enrollment
7 of the pupil.
8 The parent or legal guardian of a pupil may be excused from complying by indicating
9 that the dental screening could not be completed because of one or more of these reasons:
1 of 5

10 (A) Completion of a screening poses an undue financial burden on the parent or legal
11 guardian.
12 (B) Parents or legal guardians does not consent to a dental screening.
13 SECTION 2: Chapter 71 of the General Laws is hereby amended by inserting after
14 Section 34H, the following new section:-
15 Section 34I. A public school shall notify the parent or legal guardian of a pupil described
16 in the second paragraph of Section 57 of Chapter 71 concerning the screening required. The
17 notification shall, at a minimum, consist of a letter that includes all of the following:
18 (1) An explanation of the administrative requirements of this section.
19 (2) Information on the importance of primary teeth.
20 (3) Information on the importance of oral health to overall health as it relates to learning.
21 (4) Contact information for public health departments.
22 (5) A statement of privacy applicable under state and federal laws and regulations.
23 SECTION 3: Chapter 111 of the General Laws is hereby amended in Section 185A by
24 inserting at the end of the Section the following sentence:-
25 The department shall provide information to parents and legal guardians about programs
26 and services to access affordable dental care.
27 SECTION 4: In order to ensure uniform data collection, the department of public health,
28 in consultation with interested persons, shall develop and make available on the internet website
2 of 5

29 of the department, a standardized notification form as specified in section 2 that shall be used by
30 each school district. The standardized form shall include all of the following:
31 (1) A section that can be used by the licensed dental professional performing the dental
32 screening to record information that includes, but is not limited to, the following:
33 (A) Date of the dental screening
34 (B) School name
35 (C) Name and address of the licensed dental professional performing the screening
36 (D) Grade
37 (E) Age
38 (F) Gender
39 (G) Race/ethnicity
40 (H) Charting of untreated cavities
41 (I) Number of missing teeth
42 (J) Number of filled cavities
43 (K) Presence of sealants on permanent molars
44 (L) Treatment urgency
45 (2) A section in which the parent or legal guardian of a pupil can indicate the reason why
46 a screening could not be completed by marking the box next to the appropriate reason. The
